Answer: The problem is that you are not adding a new line character after each string in the vector. When you write the strings to the file, they are written on the same line without any separator. Therefore, when you read the file, it is treated as a single string and you get a null result.

To fix this, you need to add a new line character after each string in the vector. You can use the newLine property of the PrintWriter class to add a new line. Here is the corrected code:

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.io.FileWriter;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.PrintWriter;
import java.util.Vector;

public class VectorFile {
    public static void main(String args []) throws IOException {
        Vector<String> vc = new Vector<>();
        BufferedReader file = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("c://test1.txt"));
        PrintWriter out = new PrintWriter(new FileWriter("c://test3.txt"));
        String s;
        while ((s = file.readLine()) != null) {
            vc.add(s);
        }
        file.close();
        System.out.println(vc.size());
        for(int i=0; i<vc.size(); i++){
            out.println((String) vc.get(i));
        }
        out.close();
    }
}
```

In this corrected code, I have used PrintWriter instead of FileWriter. The println method of PrintWriter automatically adds a new line character after each string. This should solve your problem.

Note: The FileWriter and PrintWriter classes in Java automatically use the platform's default line separator. Therefore, you don't need to manually add a new line character. The println method of PrintWriter automatically adds a new line character.

Also, I have changed the Vector to Vector<String> to make it more type-safe.

This should solve your problem.
